      <body>
         <div n="4292" type="letter"><head>4292. Robert Southey to <ref type="a" target="people.html#RickmanSusannah">Susannah Rickman</ref>, <date when="1824-12-12">12 December 1824</date>
            <note type="headnote" place="foot" resp="editors">Address: To/ Mrs Rickman<lb/>
               Endorsement: R Southey to SR/ 24 <lb/>
               MS: The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, Wilson Library, James Saxon Childers Papers. ALS; 3p.<lb/>
               Unpublished.</note></head>
            
           <opener> 
              <dateline><address><placeName><ref type="m" target="places.html#Keswick">Keswick</ref>.</placeName></address><date when="1824-12-12"> 12 Dec. 1824</date></dateline>
            
           <salute> My dear Madam</salute></opener>
            <p rend="indent1">I must not send off the conclusion of a five weeks journal,<note n="1" place="foot" resp="editors">A fair copy of the journal Southey kept on his trip to the Low Countries in 1815. It was later published as <title>Journal of a Tour in the Netherlands in the Autumn of 1815</title> (1902).</note> without once more thanking you for all your kindness to <ref type="m" target="people.html#SoutheyBertha">Bertha</ref>. She will bring home with her much improvement of every kind, as well as a large stock of delightful recollections. Her visit has extended to an unreasonable length of time, – but I hope that some convoy will be found for her &#38; <ref type="m" target="people.html#SoutheyEdithMay">her sister</ref> in the course of February. We are beginning to be a little impatient of their long absence. The house does not seem like itself in winter evenings without them.</p>
            <p rend="indent1">My next Journal<note n="2" place="foot" resp="editors">This journal described Southey’s trip to France, Italy, Switzerland, Germany and the Low Countries in May–August 1817.</note> enters upon a wider circuit, &#38; thro a greater variety of scenes. I shall begin to transcribe it without delay, glad to have a motive for so doing in the hope that it may afford you some entertainment.</p>
           <p rend="indent1"> With the kindest remembrances from <ref type="m" target="people.html#FrickerEdith">M<hi rend="sup">rs</hi> S.</ref> &#38; her sisters.<note n="3" place="foot" resp="editors"><ref type="m" target="people.html#FrickerSarah">Sara Coleridge</ref> and <ref type="m" target="people.html#FrickerMary">Mary Lovell</ref>.</note></p>
           <closer><salute rend="indent1"> I remain</salute>
           <salute rend="indent2"> Dear Madam</salute>
        <salute rend="indent3">    Yrs very faithfully</salute>
           <signed rend="indent5"> Robert Southey.</signed></closer>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
